column6: N R Nygard; K S Giacoletto; C Bono; J Gorka; S Kompelli; B D Schwartz
column9: Peptide binding to surface class II molecules is the major pathway of formation of immunogenic class II-peptide complexes for viable antigen presenting cells.
column85: Peptide-MHC complex on the cell surface was detected by an anti-peptide rabbit antiserum that is able to bind the peptide both in its free and MHC bound forms. Authors find that binding is dependent on temperature, but not on cell metabolism, due to the finding that the presence of several cell metabolism inhibitors or with fixed cells, complex formation is not affected, implying that the majority of complexes form at the cell surface, without the need of endocytic processes.

column6: N R Nygard; K S Giacoletto; C Bono; J Gorka; S Kompelli; B D Schwartz
column9: Peptide binding to surface class II molecules is the major pathway of formation of immunogenic class II-peptide complexes for viable antigen presenting cells.
column85: Peptide-MHC complex formation is dependent on temperature, as it is found on the surface of both live or fixed cells. Stabilization of the MHC alpha/beta heterodimer by peptide binding is also temperature dependent.  Solid-phase immobilized peptide is bound by soluble MHC molecules.

column6: N R Nygard; K S Giacoletto; C Bono; J Gorka; S Kompelli; B D Schwartz
column9: Peptide binding to surface class II molecules is the major pathway of formation of immunogenic class II-peptide complexes for viable antigen presenting cells.
column85: Peptide-MHC complex on the cell surface was detected by an anti-peptide rabbit antiserum that is able to bind the peptide both in its free and MHC bound forms. Authors find that dissociation is dependent on temperature, as is seen with binding kinetics.

column23: The following refers to the epitope id as found in the original FIMM database: P000694 The strain is specified in neither the paper nor the references cited in the paper. IMGT database gives another strain, A/Aichi/2/68 H3N2 (X31) (source SwissProt ID P03437).

column6: P E Posch; C K Hurley; A Geluk; T H Ottenhoff
column9: The impact of DR3 microvariation on peptide binding: the combinations of specific DR beta residues critical to binding differ for different peptides.
column23: This epitope is known to bind HLA DR(alpha, beta1)*0302 but not HLA DR(alpha, beta1)*0301.
column85: DAP.3 (murine fibroblast) cells were co-transfected with DRalpha- and DRbeta-chain cDNA constructs in RSV.3 plasmids. Stable transfectants expressing high levels of HLA-DR were selected by sterile cell sorting and then cultured with long-chain biotinylated peptide (the epitope). Binding was measured on a Becton-Dickinson FacStar Plus after addition of propidium iodide to exclude unhealthy and dead cells.

column6: C Gelder; M Davenport; M Barnardo; T Bourne; J Lamb; B Askonas; A Hill; K Welsh
column9: Six unrelated HLA-DR-matched adults recognize identical CD4+ T cell epitopes from influenza A haemagglutinin that are not simply peptides with high HLA-DR binding affinities.
column23: Epitope HA 87 was identified using CD4+ T cell lines derived from DR0701, 1501 adults following influenza subunit vaccination and represents a region of hemagglutinin free from extentsive drift mutation.
column85: A competitive ELISA using biotinylated invariant chain peptide (li) was performed to examine whether the observed CD4+ T cell-HA epitope recognition pattern was a consequence of HA 87-102 simply having a high binding affinity for DRB1*0701.  No direct relationship between relative binding strength and the magnitude of T cell response was found.  IC(50) for HA 87-102 was 21,200 nM.  The mean proliferative response was 17,000cpm.

column9: Recognition of the influenza hemagglutinin by class II MHC-restricted T lymphocytes and antibodies. I. Site definition and implications for antigen presentation and T lymphocyte recognition.

column6: S Wu; J Gorski
column9: Polymorphism at beta 85 and not beta 86 of HLA-DR1 is predominantly responsible for restricting the nature of the anchor side chain: implication for concerted effects of class II MHC polymorphism.
column23: Epitope MP19-31 was previously defined. No specific strain is cited in the reference, a representative ID that includes the epitope sequence is provided here.
column85: Soluble HLA-DR1 variants, DR1VG (Val85Gly86) and DR1VV (Val85Val86) were tested for their ability to bind FITC-labeled peptide MP19-31.  The MP19-31 peptide was able to bind both DR1 variants equally well.  The specificity of this interaction was confirmed using excessive amounts of unlabeled MP19-31 as competitor.  Percent binding of DR1 variants to peptide was also evaluated over a range of peptide concentrations (0-800nM).  Binding affinities for all three variants for this peptide were similar and plateaued at approximately 600nM (Figure 2).

column6: S Wu; J Gorski
column9: Polymorphism at beta 85 and not beta 86 of HLA-DR1 is predominantly responsible for restricting the nature of the anchor side chain: implication for concerted effects of class II MHC polymorphism.
column23: Epitope MP19-31 was previously defined. No specific strain is cited in the reference, a representative ID that includes the epitope sequence is provided here.
column85: Soluble HLA-DR1 variant, DR1AV (Ala85Val86) was tested for its ability to bind FITC-labeled peptide MP19-31.  The MP19-31 peptide was able to bind this DR1 variant and the specificity of this interaction was confirmed using excessive amounts of unlabeled MP19-31 as competitor.

column85: The relative importance of residues within the P1 anchor site of peptide MP19-31 was tested by conducting binding affinities of DR1 variants to wild-type MP19-31, as well as analogs with substitutions at the P1 site. column6: Eddie A James; Antonis K Moustakas; Deanna Berger; Laurie Huston; George K Papadopoulos; William W Kwok
column9: Definition of the peptide binding motif within DRB1*1401 restricted epitopes by peptide competition and structural modeling.
column85: To determine the amino acid preferences for the binding pockets of DR1401, a panel of substituted peptide analogs was synthesized representing obligatory anchor residues for pocket 1and general classes of amino acids for pockets 4, 6, and 9. Pocket 1 preferred Met, Leu, Ile, and Val but also tolerated Phe. Pocket 4 preferred Met, Ser, Leu, Ala, Asn, and His but also tolerated Asp and Gln. Pocket 6 preferred His and Arg but also tolerated Ser, Gln, Ala, Leu, and Pro. Pocket 9 preferred Met and Ile but also tolerated Tyr, Ala, Ser and Gln.

The formation of the complex is in a 1:1 stoichiometry and not depend on metal ions.

column6: Yiwei Zhao; Zhong Li; Sandra J Drozd; Yi Guo; Walid Mourad; Hongmin Li
column9: Crystal structure of Mycoplasma arthritidis mitogen complexed with HLA-DR1 reveals a novel superantigen fold and a dimerized superantigen-MHC complex.
column85: The crystal structure contains the MHC/epitope complex bound to the superantigen (SAG) Mycoplasma arthritidis-derived mitogen (MAM). SAG PDB chain is D (and H). There are two SAG/MHC/Epitope complexes in the asymmetrical unit. The two SAG molecules interact and form an asymmetrical dimer through their C-terminal domains, cross-linking the two MHC/Epitope complexes. The analysis was based on the first complex, but the results are also applicable to the second complex. Residues that had a well ordered electron density and were included in the final model are: MHC chain alpha (PDB chain A) residues 1-181; MHC chain beta (PDB chain B) residues 1-190; epitope (PDB chain C) residues 306-318; SAG (PDB chain D) residues 1-213.

column6: Limin Wang; Yiwei Zhao; Zhong Li; Yi Guo; Lindsay L Jones; David M Kranz; Walid Mourad; Hongmin Li
column9: Crystal structure of a complete ternary complex of TCR, superantigen and peptide-MHC.
column85: There is TCR molecule in the crystal structure bound to a superantigen (SAG) molecule. The TCR does not interact with the MHC/Epitope. The TCR used was a TCR 2C variant (Vbeta8.2 Valpha3.1) that contains six mutations A: L43P, W82R, I118N; B: G17E, G42E, L81S. These mutations have been shown to increase the stability of the single chain TCR. The crystal structure contains the TCR/MHC/epitope complex bound to the superantigen (SAG) Mycoplasma arthritidis mitogen (MAM). There are two complexes in the crystallographic asymmetric unit. PDB chains for each complex are: Complex I : MHC alpha-chain: A, MHC beta-chain: B, epitope chain: C, TCR alpha-chain: I, TCR beta-chain: J, SAG chain: G. Complex II : MHC alpha-chain: D, MHC beta-chain: E, epitope chain: F, TCR alpha-chain: K, TCR beta-chain: L, SAG chain: H.

column9: DRB1*12:01 presents a unique subset of epitopes by preferring aromatics in pocket 9.
column85: Relative binding affinity (RBA) values were calculated in a biotin-based competition assay. IC50 values were calculated from the resulting curves as the peptide concentration needed for 50% inhibition of reference peptide binding. Arginine substitutions at residues 43, 46, 48, and 51 prevented peptide binding, implying that these represent anchor positions for binding to DR1201. The spacing of these residues implicates 43M as the P1 anchor, 46L as the P4 anchor, 48T as the P6 anchor, and 51I as the P9 anchor.
